      <h1 class="text-2xl text-slate-900">The OpenData Manifesto</h1>

      <p>
        Databases today are open source and commoditized. But running databases is still hard.
        So you either pay vendors who enjoy 80% margins, or you hire specialized
        SREs to babysit database clusters. Either way, running databases consumes 5–10% of
        your revenue. The real cost of your databases today is not in the code, its in the
        operations.
      </p>

      <p>
        OpenData is fixing this imbalance. Thanks to object storage, we now have durable,
        globally addressable storage that makes radically simpler database architectures
        possible. What's more, the work needed to use object storage optimally is
        substantially similar across modern databases: smart caching and batching coupled
        with correct metadata management. OpenData leverages this to build multiple databases
        on a shared core. Bespoke operational know how disappears. Fewer people are needed to
        run many databases. Operational costs collapse.
      </p>

      <p>
        We are building a collection of databases designed natively for object storage.
        Each database is focused on one usecase. All databases share:
      </p>

      <ul class="list-disc pl-6">
        <li><b>a common core</b>, so operational expertise transfers across every database </li>
        <li><b>common tooling</b>, so you have one operational model to learn </li>
        <li><b>open data formats and MIT licensing</b>, so there is no vendor lock-in </li>
      </ul>

      <p>
        We're making it practical for small teams to run their own databases again. The future
        belongs to those who own their infrastructure without being owned by it.
      </p>
      <p>
        <b>Join us.</b>
      </p>

